7. How do you manage permissions in PowerApps?

ğŸ‘‰ Yes, Iâ€™ve worked with permission handling in multiple projects.In Power Apps, permissions are usually managed in two ways:
â€” One is at the data source level (SharePoint or Dataverse), 
â€” Another one is app level using role-based logic.

ğŸ‘‰ In SharePoint-based apps (Steelcase Inventory App):
â€” I used SharePoint list permissions. For example, item-level permissions were applied through Power Automate, 
â€” when a new item was created, the flow would break inheritance and give the creator full control, and assign read-only rights to a specific group.
â€” Inside the app, I also used the User() function to check the logged-in user and apply conditional visibility.
  Example: Only managers could see the â€œApproveâ€ button, others couldnâ€™t.

ğŸ‘‰ In Dataverse-based apps (Steelcase Order Tracking App):
â€” Here it was more structured. I configured security roles in Dataverse, 
â€” Procurement Manager had approve rights, while Procurement Agent could only create and edit records.
â€” In the Model-Driven App, this worked automatically because security roles control what tables, fields, and rows each role can access.
â€” On top of that, I sometimes added Power Fx conditions in Canvas screens for hiding/showing controls based on role.















